  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I sell my Brisbane investment property before or after I retire to reduce CGT?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For most Brisbane investors approaching retirement, triggering the capital gain in the first full financial year of retirement, when taxable income is at its lowest, is the single most powerful CGT timing decision available. Each year of full-time employment that you bring the sale forward typically adds tens of thousands of dollars in extra tax because the gain is added on top of your wage at marginal rates. The exception is where you can offset the gain with deductible super contributions or carry-forward concessional cap room while still working. Get individual tax advice before you sign a contract."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does the CGT event happen at contract date or settlement date?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under ATO rules, the CGT event for a property sale happens on the contract date, not the settlement date. This is one of the most common mistakes Brisbane sellers make. If you sign a contract on 28 June 2026 with settlement in August, the gain falls into the 2025-26 financial year even though the money does not arrive until 2026-27. For sellers using retirement timing to reduce CGT, this means contracts signed in the last weeks of June can pull a gain into a high-income year you were trying to avoid. Sellers wanting the gain in the next financial year should not sign contracts until 1 July."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I use carry-forward concessional super contributions to reduce CGT on selling my Brisbane investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, if your total super balance was under $500,000 on the previous 30 June and you have unused concessional cap from any of the past five financial years, you can make catch-up concessional contributions in the year of sale. For Brisbane sellers in their late 50s and early 60s with a large capital gain coming, a lump sum personal deductible contribution can claw back a meaningful portion of the gain at marginal rates while only paying 15% contributions tax inside super. The carry-forward window is rolling, so unused cap from five years ago drops off if not used. This should be confirmed with a registered tax agent before contracts are signed."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the 50% CGT discount and when do I qualify?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Individual Australian residents who have held an asset for more than 12 months receive a 50% discount on the assessable capital gain. For a Brisbane investor selling a property held for 20 years, that means only half of the gross gain (after deducting cost base, including stamp duty paid at purchase, capital improvements, and incidental costs of sale) is added to taxable income. The 12-month rule is calculated from the day after the contract date of purchase to the day before the contract date of sale. Signing a sale contract one day too early can cost the full discount on the entire gain. The discount does not apply inside an SMSF in pension phase, where capital gains may be effectively tax-free instead."
      }
    }
  ]
};
